namic loading, defineClass might still be relevant. The tests in the repo are skipped for native, which seems risky since our requirements don’t allow that. I wonder about simulating NoClassDefFoundError from getDeclaredMethods on a statically present class.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring classloading options**\\n\\nI’m considering using a class with a method that requires an optional dependency, which isn't available at runtime. In the native image, all classes must be included. Adding a class file resource as a test dependency might work, but I'm wondering if compiling with an optional dependency and then removing it is feasible. It seems like using Java Proxy isn't the right approach either. Fallback branches seem challenging in native environments. Yet the user insists that tests must run in native; I might be overthinking this! Maybe the repo’s native tests are actually using JVM mode?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_jy9IpQ4RfhJNhpyMppBKWodp|fc_00a21d91f616a7cc0169f2bd428308819c8dda42c4611c18db", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git diff --check -- tests/src/org.apache.parquet/parquet-jackson/1.12.2/src/test/java/org_apache_parquet/parquet_jackson/ClassUtilTest.java tests/src/org.apache.parquet/parquet-jackson/1.12.2/src/test/java/org_apache_parquet/parquet_jackson/Parquet_jacksonTest.java", "timeout": 30}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"git diff --check -- tests/src/org.apache.parquet/parquet-jackson/1.12.2/src/test/java/org_apache_parquet/parquet_jackson/ClassUtilTest.java tests/src/org.apache.parquet/parquet-jackson/1.12.2/src/test/java/org_apache_parquet/parquet_jackson/Parquet_jacksonTest.java\",\"timeout\":30}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 599, "output": 1013, "cacheRead": 40960, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42572, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777515826568, "respons